120
00:04:45,860 --> 00:04:46,920
Next question.

121
00:04:48,480 --> 00:04:50,190
Is there anything in relativity

122
00:04:50,190 --> 00:04:51,900
to limit the relative velocity?

123
00:04:52,180 --> 00:04:54,280
Or can two coordinate points,

124
00:04:54,280 --> 00:04:55,340
let's just call them galaxies,

125
00:04:56,180 --> 00:05:00,420
can two galaxies have a relative velocity greater than c,

126
00:05:00,600 --> 00:05:01,660
greater than the speed of light?

127
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:03,000
The answer is yes.

128
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:04,460
If they're far enough apart,

129
00:05:04,460 --> 00:05:07,140
this is just the Hubble law,

130
00:05:07,220 --> 00:05:13,280
and the Hubble law holds on distances which are much,

131
00:05:14,099 --> 00:05:16,200
which may be arbitrarily large,

132
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:17,040
we don't know for sure,

133
00:05:17,260 --> 00:05:19,630
but there's nothing wrong with extending

134
00:05:19,630 --> 00:05:22,000
the Hubble law out to distances

135
00:05:22,180 --> 00:05:28,500
such that velocity is equal to Hubble times distance.

136
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:33,120
If space is as flat as it appears to be,

137
00:05:33,120 --> 00:05:34,540
and it does appear to be flat,

138
00:05:35,300 --> 00:05:38,820
then there's no obvious bound,

139
00:05:38,820 --> 00:05:42,120
certainly nothing within observation,

140
00:05:42,960 --> 00:05:44,920
no obvious bound on distances.

141
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:47,240
If distance is big enough,

142
00:05:47,240 --> 00:05:49,380
then the velocity,

143
00:05:49,380 --> 00:05:51,440
the relative velocity of us,

144
00:05:52,180 --> 00:05:55,060
to some distant galaxy will exceed the speed of light.

145
00:05:55,820 --> 00:05:56,980
Can't do anything about it,

146
00:05:56,980 --> 00:05:57,300
it's true.

147
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:01,100
Einstein never said that that was impossible.

148
00:06:02,160 --> 00:06:03,060
Let's put it this way,

149
00:06:03,060 --> 00:06:04,400
what he would say was impossible

150
00:06:04,920 --> 00:06:06,860
is for one thing to pass

151
00:06:06,860 --> 00:06:08,800
another right in front of your nose

152
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:10,440
at faster than the speed of light.

153
00:06:10,740 --> 00:06:12,810
It doesn't say anything about very

154
00:06:12,810 --> 00:06:14,880
distant things moving relative to each other

155
00:06:14,880 --> 00:06:16,140
where they're greater than the speed of light.

156
00:06:16,540 --> 00:06:17,340
But of course,

157
00:06:17,340 --> 00:06:19,260
if something is moving faster than

158
00:06:19,260 --> 00:06:21,180
the speed of light away from you,

159
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:23,500
and assuming that it continues to do that,

160
00:06:23,720 --> 00:06:26,040
then it can never send a message to you,

161
00:06:28,960 --> 00:06:32,380
because if it's moving away from you

162
00:06:32,380 --> 00:06:35,800
with faster than the speed of light,

163
00:06:39,039 --> 00:06:41,479
then light rays which are sent to the left

164
00:06:41,479 --> 00:06:43,920
and light waves which are sent to the right

165
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:46,310
will be both swept along with the

166
00:06:46,310 --> 00:06:48,700
motion and effectively be moving away from you.

167
00:06:49,480 --> 00:06:49,960
So...

168
00:06:51,180 --> 00:06:54,190
There is no such cosmic limitation on whether

169
00:06:54,190 --> 00:06:57,200
distant things can be moving away from you.

170
00:06:57,420 --> 00:06:59,900
The place where they're moving with the speed

171
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:02,380
of light relative to you is a horizon.

172
00:07:02,680 --> 00:07:03,220
Yeah?

173
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:06,030
Wouldn't the light ray sent

174
00:07:06,030 --> 00:07:08,460
in the reverse direction be backward?

175
00:07:08,760 --> 00:07:09,320
Right,

176
00:07:09,320 --> 00:07:09,700
yeah.

177
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:13,880
Wouldn't that still be traveling at sea towards you,

178
00:07:13,900 --> 00:07:15,750
but stretched in wavelength to

179
00:07:15,750 --> 00:07:17,600
where it is no longer light?

180
00:07:17,880 --> 00:07:19,680
It's actually moving away from you.

181
00:07:20,120 --> 00:07:20,760
Well,

182
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:21,160
let's put it this way.

183
00:07:21,180 --> 00:07:21,660
Let's put it this way.

184
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:22,760
Let's put it this way.

185
00:07:23,840 --> 00:07:24,320
Okay,

186
00:07:24,320 --> 00:07:26,580
the light ray is moving that way,

187
00:07:27,159 --> 00:07:29,519
but space is growing faster

188
00:07:29,519 --> 00:07:31,880
than the light ray can overcome.

189
00:07:33,080 --> 00:07:33,260
Okay?

190
00:07:35,879 --> 00:07:36,359
So,

191
00:07:36,359 --> 00:07:38,260
there's a model for this which I like.

192
00:07:38,460 --> 00:07:40,020
It's a model which I

193
00:07:40,020 --> 00:07:41,580
invented in order to explain inflation.

194
00:07:42,939 --> 00:07:46,660
But let me explain what the model is.

195
00:07:47,060 --> 00:07:47,340
Okay.

196
00:07:50,719 --> 00:07:52,340
Imagine you have a line.

197
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:55,800
And now you start stretching the line.

198
00:07:55,900 --> 00:07:57,300
The line is made up out of atoms.

199
00:07:57,680 --> 00:07:58,040
Okay?

200
00:07:58,060 --> 00:07:59,480
The line is made up out of atoms.

201
00:08:02,360 --> 00:08:04,040
And now you start stretching it.

202
00:08:04,100 --> 00:08:04,560
What happens?

203
00:08:05,300 --> 00:08:08,730
Eventually it'll break because the distance between the atoms

204
00:08:08,730 --> 00:08:12,160
will grow larger than the atomic forces can handle.

205
00:08:12,640 --> 00:08:16,700
But we also have secretly a source of extra atoms.

206
00:08:16,700 --> 00:08:18,610
And every time two atoms get

207
00:08:18,610 --> 00:08:20,520
further apart than a certain distance,

208
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,140
we put another one in.

209
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:23,980
Everywhere that it happens,

210
00:08:24,220 --> 00:08:25,360
everywhere that it happens,

211
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:27,920
we keep filling it up with more and more atoms,

212
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:29,920
so that the line,

213
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:30,240
yeah,

214
00:08:31,859 --> 00:08:34,000
so that the line continues to grow,

215
00:08:34,999 --> 00:08:37,559
constantly being resupplied with atoms.

216
00:08:38,460 --> 00:08:38,900
Okay?

217
00:08:38,940 --> 00:08:39,140
Now,

218
00:08:39,140 --> 00:08:41,240
it's not atoms really that we want to think about,

219
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:42,640
but it's a good model for it.

220
00:08:43,539 --> 00:08:43,980
Then,

221
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:48,680
this line will grow,

222
00:08:48,680 --> 00:08:49,560
first of all,

223
00:08:49,560 --> 00:08:50,660
according to Hubble's law.

224
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:53,140
It will also grow exponentially.

225
00:08:53,760 --> 00:08:56,980
The distance between any two points will grow exponentially.

226
00:08:58,100 --> 00:09:00,860
And there will be some distance beyond which

227
00:09:02,100 --> 00:09:03,720
two things will be receding with

228
00:09:03,720 --> 00:09:05,340
greater than the speed of light.

229
00:09:05,820 --> 00:09:07,980
But if you go to those places,

230
00:09:10,460 --> 00:09:11,560
you can ask,

231
00:09:11,560 --> 00:09:14,120
supposing here's where the velocity of separation

232
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:16,680
gets to be about the speed of light,

233
00:09:16,700 --> 00:09:18,080
if you go to the left

234
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:19,460
and you send a light beam,

235
00:09:19,620 --> 00:09:21,580
you can still certainly send a light beam this way,

236
00:09:21,660 --> 00:09:23,120
and you can send a light beam that way.

237
00:09:23,580 --> 00:09:25,790
The only problem is the

238
00:09:25,790 --> 00:09:28,000
atoms are filling in so fast

239
00:09:28,719 --> 00:09:31,469
that the distance between you and

240
00:09:31,469 --> 00:09:34,220
where the light ray has gotten to

241
00:09:34,220 --> 00:09:39,680
is growing faster than the light ray can overcome.

242
00:09:40,900 --> 00:09:42,000
Can I ask you a question?

243
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:42,440
Yeah.

244
00:09:42,580 --> 00:09:43,860
Does the ordinary,

245
00:09:43,860 --> 00:09:46,680
does the relativistic form like this,

246
00:09:46,680 --> 00:09:48,480
in order for the addition of velocities hold?

247
00:09:48,940 --> 00:09:49,400
Locally,

248
00:09:49,400 --> 00:09:49,960
at a point,

249
00:09:49,960 --> 00:09:50,300
yes.

250
00:09:50,520 --> 00:09:51,520
In other words,

251
00:09:51,520 --> 00:09:52,580
if we have two observers,

252
00:09:52,580 --> 00:09:53,740
three observers,

253
00:09:54,020 --> 00:09:55,520
and they all pass each other,

254
00:09:55,520 --> 00:09:57,000
one after another after another...

255
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:57,840
But it only holds in that,

256
00:09:57,840 --> 00:09:59,530
but it doesn't hold in the

257
00:09:59,530 --> 00:10:01,220
case of velocities exceeding the speed.

258
00:10:01,220 --> 00:10:01,380
Yeah,

259
00:10:01,380 --> 00:10:01,760
that's right.

260
00:10:01,760 --> 00:10:04,240
You have to go back to the first principles again.

261
00:10:04,520 --> 00:10:08,840
There you have to use some more fancy geometric...

262
00:10:09,500 --> 00:10:11,590
If you have two photons

263
00:10:11,590 --> 00:10:13,680
that are radiated from a point,

264
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:16,420
their separation velocity is 2c.

265
00:10:17,220 --> 00:10:17,640
Yes.

266
00:10:18,500 --> 00:10:19,820
As seen by you.

267
00:10:20,100 --> 00:10:20,980
As seen by you.

268
00:10:21,180 --> 00:10:21,580
Yeah,

269
00:10:21,580 --> 00:10:23,530
but you could send something out with three

270
00:10:23,530 --> 00:10:25,480
quarters of the speed of light that way,

271
00:10:25,620 --> 00:10:26,940
and three quarters of the

272
00:10:26,940 --> 00:10:28,260
speed of light the other way,

273
00:10:29,260 --> 00:10:31,950
and their relative separation to you will seem to

274
00:10:31,950 --> 00:10:34,640
be one and a half times the speed of light,

275
00:10:35,360 --> 00:10:37,620
but to one of them looking at the other,

276
00:10:37,620 --> 00:10:38,320
uh-uh,

277
00:10:38,320 --> 00:10:39,580
it looks less than the speed of light.

278
00:10:39,860 --> 00:10:40,740
So this is different.

279
00:10:41,480 --> 00:10:45,440
And a photon itself doesn't have an inertial reference rate.

280
00:10:46,040 --> 00:10:46,560
Well,

281
00:10:46,560 --> 00:10:47,720
it's moving with the speed of light.

282
00:10:51,180 --> 00:10:51,700
So,

283
00:10:51,700 --> 00:10:54,400
the point is you can't answer questions

284
00:10:54,400 --> 00:10:57,100
like this just using ordinary special relativity.

285
00:10:57,360 --> 00:10:58,460
You have to use general relativity,

